[Good news and not so good news.
The good news is:
- no newly confirmed cases of wild poliovirus type 1 (WPV1) in any country around the world in the past week.
- no newly confirmed cases of circulating vaccine derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) reported from Syria, with most recent date of onset 21 Sep 2017.
The not so good news:
- advanced notification of 5 cases of cVDPV2 associated disease reported in Tanganika province, Dem Republic of the Congo.
- 3 new WPV1 positive environmental samples reported from Afghanistan. 1 each from Kandahar province, Hilmand province and Nangarhar province.
- 4 new WPV1 positive environmental samples reported from Pakistan. 3 from Sindh province, 1 from Khyber Pakthunkhwa province.

See section [2] below for a discussion re: positive environmental samples. A question that recurrently comes to my mind when reviewing these updates is whether the absence of reports on results of environmental sampling in Nigeria is synonymous with no positive environmental samples have been identified versus no environmental samples have been evaluated.

The persistent finding of positive environmental samples in Pakistan and Afghanistan continues to be disconcerting as it is an indicator of continued circulation of the WPV1 in the countries and similar to the discussion in the below article, one can't help but wonder if cases are being missed by the AFP (acute flaccid paralysis) surveillance activities.

A map showing the locations of all confirmed cases of polio (both WPV as well as cVDPV associated) can be found at: http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

HealthMap/ProMED maps can be found at:
